Mission 1: AtmosphereWatch CubeSat
Mission idea
Students use the CubeSat to collect temperature, pressure, and humidity data at different locations or elevations to model how atmospheric conditions change and how those changes can be monitored like a weather or Earth-observing satellite.
Driving question
How can a CubeSat monitor changing atmospheric conditions to help people better understand weather and environmental systems?
Mission objectives
Measure temperature, humidity, and pressure over time


Compare data across locations, heights, or times of day


Identify environmental patterns and possible hazard indicators


Evaluate how well the CubeSat design protects and supports reliable sensing


Example student activities
Collect indoor vs. outdoor data


Take data at ground level vs. upper floor/stairwell


Monitor a sealed container vs. open air


Compare sunny vs. shaded conditions


Graph pressure, humidity, and temperature trends


NGSS alignment
MS-ESS3-2: Use environmental data to discuss hazard monitoring


MS-ESS3-3: Design a method to monitor environmental conditions


MS-ESS3-5: Discuss temperature trends and environmental change


MS-PS1-4: Relate heating/cooling to temperature changes


MS-ETS1-1 to 1-4: Define the problem, test designs, analyze data, improve the CubeSat

